## 3. Component Patterns

### 3.1 Avoid Class Components

**❌ Don't:**

```typescript
class MyComponent extends React.Component<Props, State> {
  constructor(props: Props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { count: 0 };
  }

  render() {
    return <div>{this.state.count}</div>;
  }
}
```

**✅ Do:**

```typescript
const MyComponent = ({ initialCount = 0 }: Props) => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(initialCount);

  return <div>{count}</div>;
};
```

### 3.2 Avoid Compose Pattern (HOCs)

**❌ Don't:**

```typescript
const MyComponent = ({ data, querySearch, updateQuerySearch }: Props) => {
  return <div>...</div>;
};

export default compose(withData, withQuerySearch, withAnalytics)(MyComponent);
```

**✅ Do:**

```typescript
const MyComponent = (props: Props) => {
  // Use hooks instead
  const data = useData();
  const { querySearch, updateQuerySearch } = useQuerySearch();
  const { trackEvent } = useAnalytics();

  return <div>...</div>;
};

export default MyComponent;
```

**Exception:** `withQuerySearch` is still used in legacy code but should be migrated to `useQuerySearch` hook for new components.

### 3.3 Functional Component Best Practices

**✅ Do:**

```typescript
// 1. Keep components focused and single-responsibility
// 2. Extract complex logic into custom hooks
// 3. Use composition over inheritance
// 4. Keep render logic clean and readable

const UserProfile = ({ userId }: Props) => {
  const { user, isLoading } = useUserData(userId);
  const { updateUser } = useUserActions();

  if (isLoading) {
    return <Spinner />;
  }

  return (
    <Box>
      <UserHeader user={user} />
      <UserDetails user={user} onUpdate={updateUser} />
    </Box>
  );
};
```

